<div id="review_139687495" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/139687495" />
    <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly"><img alt="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349701607p2/2190636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/139687495?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly">Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer139687495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11606401757415755915">My brother-in-law loves to spend his weekend drinking with his buddies. They drink and swap tales. My mother, sister, wife, our househelps and a lot of women I know all have their favorite soap operas, movies, gossips and daily topics for discussion. A brother of mine is a voracious reader; the other, addicted to historical trivia. All these are just varied ways to satisfy the great human need for stories.<br/><br/>Great story, this novel with a title taken from T.S. Eliot&apos;s &quot;The Waste Land,&quot; that part wh</span>
  <span id="freeText11606401757415755915" style="display:none">My brother-in-law loves to spend his weekend drinking with his buddies. They drink and swap tales. My mother, sister, wife, our househelps and a lot of women I know all have their favorite soap operas, movies, gossips and daily topics for discussion. A brother of mine is a voracious reader; the other, addicted to historical trivia. All these are just varied ways to satisfy the great human need for stories.<br /><br />Great story, this novel with a title taken from T.S. Eliot's "The Waste Land," that part which somberly speaks about a "decayed hole among the mountains" where the grass is singing in the faint moonlight. It starts at the end, someone is found dead, then Doris Lessing slowly unveils the life of this death. Like me, you will have your guesses as to by whose hands she had died, and like me, you will be wrong about it, even if you are intelligent. And especially if you are intelligent.<br /><br />This was Lessing's very first novel, published thirteen years before her most famous work, "The Golden Notebook," yet she had written it like a true master. She tells a story and you listen. You don't yawn, or put it off for a while because you have other things to do. Lessing is telling the story of this housewife, living in an open country in South Africa, with her decent but inept husband, their crumbling house with no attic, their poverty, and a black slave named Moses, so you read and listen. On and on, you do that until it is finished and you go back to the dead, this poor Mary Turner who had been so alive within the pages of the book that you think Meryl Streep for her, and maybe Liam Neeson for her husband Dick Turner, and the black slave, well, maybe Mike Tyson, if he ever learns how to act. Then you close the book, sighing contentedly, like your mother after she had finished watching her favorite tv soap.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11606401757415755915" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


